$DATUM Both formates were synthesized from the corresponding alcohols,
(Z)-9-tetradecenol and (Z)-11-hexadecenol (Pherobank, The Netherlands).
Dicyclohexylcarbodiimide (DCC, 0.38 g, 1.84 mmol) was added to a solution
of formic acid (70 μl, 1.84 mmol) in dried dichloromethane (6 ml), before
(Z)-9-tetradecenol (0.3 g, 1.41 mmol) was added, along with
4-dimethylaminopyridine (DMAP) (catalytic amount). The same procedure was
used with (Z)-11-hexadecenol (0.3 g, 1.25 mmol), adjusting the amount of
reagents to maintain the same molar ratios (Neises and Steglich, 1978).
The mixture was stirred for 4 hr under a nitrogen atmosphere at ambient
temperature, before the crude product was diluted with dichloromethane
(15 ml), filtered, and washed with a saturated solution of NaCl. After
evaporation of the solvent, the residue was purified by flash
chromatography (silica gel, hexane-ethyl acetate 9:1) to obtain
(Z)-9-tetradecenyl formate and 302 mg of (Z)-11-hexadecenyl formate
(purity by GC-MS, for both formates). (Z)-9-tetradecenyl formate. Yield
304 mg (90%). Purity: 99%. 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3), δ (ppm): 8.06 (s, 1H,
OCOH); 5.30-5.39 (m, 2H, CH = CH); 4.16 (t, J=6.8 Hz, 2H, CH2O);
1.99-2.02 (m, 4H, H2C-CH = CH-CH2); 1.62-1.69 (m, 2H, H2C-CH2O);
1.26-1.37 (m, 14H, CH2); 0.89 (t, J=7.0 Hz, 3H, CH3). 13C NMR (100 MHz,
CDCl3), δ (ppm): 161.4; 130.1; 129.9; 64.3; 32.1; 29.8; 29.5; 29.3; 29.3;
28.6; 27.3; 27.1; 25.9; 22.5; 14.2. MS (EI) m/z (%): 194 (7); 138 (9);
137 (6); 124 (13); 123 (11); 111 (4); 110 (23); 109 (23); 97 (13); 96
(63); 95 (51); 83 (25); 82 (89); 81 (84); 80 (5); 79 (8); 70 (10); 69
(44); 68 (46); 67 (76); 66 (7); 57 (9); 56 (18); 55 (100); 54 (38); 43
(18); 42 (10); 41 (54).

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Protected analog 11: CDI (0.264 g, 1.63 mmol)
in THF (17 mL) was cooled to 0 °C with an ice bath under an atmosphere of
argon. Formic acid 98% (0.075 g, 1.63 mmol) was added and the solution
was stirred for 1 h. Compound 10 (0.142 g, 0.326 mmol) was added and the
solution was stirred overnight at 0 °C. The solution was concentrated and
taken up in EtOAc. The organic solution was washed with 5% NaHCO3, water
and brine. The organic solution was dried Na2SO4, filtered and
concentrated. The residue was purified by reverse phase C18
chromatography (40% MeOH to 55% MeOH:H2O) to give 0.132 g of the product
in 87% yield as an amorphous solid. Formylated compound 16: Compound 15
(0.38 g, 0.0923 mmol) was formylated as in the synthesis of analog 3. The
residue was purified by reverse phase C18 column chromatography (40% to
60% MeOH:water) to yield 0.037 g of the product in 90% yield as an
amorphous clear solid. 1H NMR Rotational isomers present, major peaks
reported when possible. (600 MHz, CD6OD) δ 8.15 (s, 0.5H), 7.84 (s,
0.5H), 7.37-7.19 (m, 10 H), 4.86 (d, 1H, J = 10.43 Hz), 4.76 (d, 1H, J =
10.25 Hz), 4.44-4.34 (m, 1H), 3.88-3.71 (m, 2H), 3.61 br d, 1H, 15,38
Hz), 3.27 (br d, 1H, 14.84 Hz), 3.13 (br s, 1H), 2.98-2.96 (m, 2H),
2.71-2.59 (m, 1H), 1.84-1.33 (m, 6H); 13C (600 MHz, CD6OD) δ 174.7,
174.5, 171.0, 164.6, 160.6, 139.9, 139.7, 136.2, 135.8, 131.2, 130.9,
130.3, 130.2, 130.1, 129.9, 129.8, 129.7, 127.8, 127.7, 78.5, 77.2, 54.2,
52.8, 50.5, 47.6, 47.4, 46.0, 37.4, 31.8, 28.7, 27.0; IR (Neat) 3250,

$DATUM N-Phthalimide-N(in)-formyl l-tryptophane HCl(g) was bubbled into a
mixture of N-phthalimide l-tryptophane (5 g, 15 mmol) in formic acid (60
mL). The mixture turned dark red and was stirred at rt for 5 h. Formic
acid was evaporated under reduced pressure and the resulting red solid
was dissolved in EtOAc and recrystallized with ether. The desired product
was obtained by filtration as yellow crystals. Yield: 90%.
N-Phthalimide-N(in)-formyl l-tryptophane, yield: 90%.x 1H NMR (CDCl3)): δ
3.70 (m, 2H, CH2), 5.33 (m, 1H, CHCH2), 7.27 (BrS, 1H, indole), 7.30 (m,
2H, indole), 7.65 (m, 2H, indole), 7.65 (m, 2H, phth), 7.85 (m, 2H,
phth), 8.29 (Brd, J = 4.0 Hz, 1H, CHO).

$DATUM (1R*,3R*,6S*,7S*,10R*)-10-Formyloxy-7-methoxy-4-azatricyclo[4.3.1.03,7]decane-
4-carboxylic acid ethyl ester (37). A soluiton of carbamate 34 (163 mg,
0.724 mmol), paraformaldehyde (28.7 mg, 0.957 mol) and formic acid (5.0
mL) was heated at 50 °C for 1.5 h. The resulting yellow solution was
cooled to rt and concentrated. The crude residue was dissolved in Et2O
(10 mL) and made basic (pH 10) with the addition of 5 N KOH. The layers
were separated and the aqueous layer was extracted with Et2O (3 × 10 mL).
The combined organic layers were dried (K2CO3), filtered and
concentrated. Purification of the crude residue by chromatography (7:3
hexane/EtOAc) gave 184 mg (90%) of 38 as a clear oil: 1H NMR (250 MHz,
CDCl3)6 δ 7.99 (s), 7.96 (s, 1 H), 5.0–4.8 (m, 1 H), 4.25–4.00 (m, 3 H),
3.80 (dd, J = 15.6, 10.7 Hz, 1 H), 3.5–3.3 (m, 1 H), 3.26 (s), 3.25 (s, 3
H), 2.6–2.4 (m, 2 H), 2.4–1.8 (m, 5 H) 1.50– 1.35 (m, 1 H), 1.26 (t, J =
7.1, Hz, 3 H), 1.23 (t, J = 7.0 Hz); 13C NMR (63 MHz, CDCl3, mixture of
conformational isomers) δ 160.5, 160.2, 155.1, 154.9, 90.4, 89.7, 72.6,
72.4, 60.7, 60.6, 58.7, 58.1, 51.5, 51.1, 47.4, 45.8, 44.9, 44.8, 42.9,
42.7, 32.2, 31.4, 26.7, 26.6, 24.9, 24.5, 14.9, 14.8; IR (CCl4) 2951,
1702, 1421, 1167 cm-1; MS (CI) m/z 284.1490 (MH, 284.1517 calcd for
C14H21NO5), 238.
